<font color="#FF0000">VETS AND PROTESTERS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Oct  7 20:16:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Whew!  This is quite an interesting site - you guys are quite a trip, not too hard to figure out from where America's aggressive power-driven personna grows, is it?  I was tempted to call this a sandbox rather than a site, but in truth, the issue is far too serious for me to be so flip. <br><br>
It is interesting to me that the overwhelming majority of posts are from men.  As a woman, I was not personally threatened by the draft in the sense of having to go to Viet Nam myself, but both of my brothers were (they ended up with high draft numbers) and all of my friends were. The war was a formative influence in my life, beginning in the sixties when I was still in high school and continuing to this day.<br><br>
By 1967 I was intensely against the war.  In the fall of 1967 I helped organize for the New Mobe on my college campus, and I went to the Pentagon that year in my first anti-war march. It was an experience I will never forget. I demonstrated against the war many many times over the next eight years, and I was arrested in San Francisco in 1971 (&quot;No business as usual&quot;) at a demonstration, experienced a trial on totally trumped-up and bogus charges the result of which was a hung jury and eventually a plea bargain for lesser charges which themselves were bogus.  My &quot;crime&quot;? Standing on street corners, in banks, and on the steps of the stock exchange  reading Mark Twain's great anti-war poem, &quot;The War Prayer&quot; to whoever would listen.  What I was charged with? Assaulting an officer and resisting arrest (he said I bit him on the shoulder but that fortunately his wife had made him wear two sets of long underwear that day, and it was right where his tac squad insignia patch was, so he didn't even have any teeth marks. . .)  What I copped to? - disturbing the peace.  90 day suspended sentence, 3 years probation and $100 fine!<br><br>
I am so proud that I was an anti-war activist in whatever way I could manage in those years.  I am proud to be able to tell my daughter that I fought against the war, and that I stood up for what was right. At the time, I wrote my parents that I believed that it was my obligation as an American citizen to do so, that that was what America was about, not being afraid to say when my country was wrong.<br><br>
What I am not so proud about was that in my youth, my arrogance at the time, my inexperience, my ignorance, I was definitely insensitive to the guys who served.  I protested then not because, as one of the posters said - how sad! - I would rather see Americans die than Asians, but because I couldn't then, as I don't now, believe that this was a war the U.S. had any business being involved in, and that *both* Americans and Vietnamese were dying in a war that was the antithesis of everything Americans purported to support - that is, self-determination - a country's right to choose its own course, whether or not it happened to be acceptable to Washington, D.C.  What we did, and attempted to do in Viet Nam remains and will always remain a major shameful episode in our history, any revisionist attempts to the contrary.<br><br>
What I know now, however, that I did not know so well then, is that the American G.I., all the guys and women who served, were also victims of that war.  Those who enlisted with the most patriotric intentions, and those who were drafted reluctantly, it didn't matter. When they returned, we blamed the victims, especially the most wounded (and I don't mean the physically wounded alone) of them, and many of us displaced our anger on them.  To the extent I was ever guilty of this, I apologize and I deeply regret it.  To a one, every vet I have ever known has spoken only of how terrible it was there, what a waste it was, and how naive he had been until he got there. I knew guys that threw back their medals, that had fragged their officers, that were just glad to be back.  These were not then, and have never been, the ones to blame for the war.<br><br>
You guys can go on calling each other names and beating each other up forever if you want to, clearly you have some need to go on defending your line in the sand.  I think it's too bad, though, because what needs to happen now is to see that we did what we had to do, for whatever reason, and if we're lucky, we've learned something in 25 years. I have been to the Wall many times, what I love about it best is that as you go there to honor the dead, you see your own reflection mingled with the names of the dead. I cry for them, I cry for them all; I cry with sadness and frustration and anger that they were sacrified, and I cry with pride that I did my part to bring the war to an end.  <br><br>

<p><code>--   (Lin ) </code><p>


